<CaseStudy
  title="Sentinel — Real-Time Anomaly Detection Agent"
  description="A four-node LangGraph agent that ingests 100+ events/sec from a Kafka stream, detects statistical anomalies via DuckDB, and generates AI root-cause reports in under 90 seconds — with a live WebSocket dashboard."
  role="AI Systems Engineer · Data Engineer"
  period="2025"
  stack={['LangGraph', 'Groq (Llama 3.3 70B)', 'DuckDB', 'Redpanda/Kafka', 'FastAPI', 'WebSocket', 'Docker']}
  outcome="<10% false-positive rate · <90s root-cause report · 100+ events/sec sustained throughput · Live WebSocket feed"
  codeUrl="https://github.com/Mprtham/Real-Time-Anomaly-Detection-Agent"
>

  <h2>The question</h2>
  <p>
    Standard anomaly detection pipelines flag an alert. Then someone has to investigate it — pulling logs, querying databases, forming a hypothesis, writing it up. That last mile often takes hours. Could an AI agent close the gap: detect the anomaly <em>and</em> produce a root-cause report fast enough to be actionable in a real-time ops context?
  </p>
  <p>
    The constraint: it had to run on commodity hardware (no GPU), process a high-velocity stream, and keep the false-positive rate low enough that on-call engineers wouldn't learn to ignore it.
  </p>

  <h2>The approach</h2>

  <h3>Stream ingestion (Redpanda/Kafka)</h3>
  <p>
    Events — simulating application metrics, user behaviour signals, and infrastructure telemetry — are produced to a Redpanda topic at 100+ events/sec. A consumer service reads from the topic and batches events into a DuckDB in-process analytical store. Redpanda was chosen over vanilla Kafka for its lower operational overhead in a single-node development context while maintaining the Kafka protocol.
  </p>

  <h3>Statistical detection (DuckDB)</h3>
  <p>
    DuckDB runs Z-score and rolling-window IQR detection directly in-process — no round trip to an external database. Detection queries run on sliding windows of the last 60 seconds of events. A signal is flagged only when both methods agree, which is the primary driver of the sub-10% false-positive rate.
  </p>

  <h3>LangGraph agent (4 nodes)</h3>
  <p>
    Once an anomaly is confirmed, the LangGraph pipeline kicks in:
  </p>
  <ul>
    <li><strong>Context node:</strong> pulls the surrounding event window and computes summary statistics</li>
    <li><strong>Hypothesis node:</strong> Groq-hosted Llama 3.3 70B generates ranked hypotheses based on the statistical pattern and event metadata</li>
    <li><strong>Evidence node:</strong> queries DuckDB for corroborating signals (correlated metrics, prior occurrences, baseline comparisons)</li>
    <li><strong>Report node:</strong> synthesises context, hypotheses, and evidence into a structured root-cause report with confidence scores and recommended actions</li>
  </ul>

