  <h2>What broke / what I'd change</h2>
  <p>
    <strong>DuckDB memory pressure at sustained throughput.</strong> DuckDB's in-process model is excellent for analytical queries but the event buffer needed careful windowing to prevent unbounded memory growth at 100+ events/sec. The fix was a scheduled compaction job that evicts events older than 10 minutes — simple but not obvious from the documentation.
  </p>
  <p>
    <strong>LLM latency is the pipeline's critical path.</strong> Groq's inference is fast (sub-second token generation), but the hypothesis and evidence nodes involve sequential LLM calls. The report latency is almost entirely inference time. The next version would parallelise the hypothesis and evidence nodes using LangGraph's built-in parallel branch support.
  </p>
  <p>
    <strong>False-positive tuning is empirical.</strong> The dual-method approach (Z-score AND IQR) was the most effective lever for reducing false positives — but the thresholds were tuned by running the system against synthetic data with known anomalies. In production, that tuning would need to happen against real traffic patterns per metric type.
  </p>

